<BaseLayout title="Starting dialysis: what to expect" description="What to bring, who you'll meet, and what actually happens when you start dialysis at St. John Biocare — with the fear taken out.">
  <article class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px">
      <a href="/kidney-health" style="font-weight:700;text-decoration:none">← Kidney Health Hub</a>
      <h1 style="margin-top:14px">Starting dialysis: what to expect</h1>
      <p class="lead">The unknown is the scariest part. Here's what actually happens — and how to prepare.</p>
      <p class="muted" style="font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from
        <a href={src}>renalcarematters.com</a>.</p>

      <h2>Seeing a kidney doctor early helps</h2>
      <p>A nephrologist is a physician who specialises in the kidneys. Patients seen by one
      <strong>before</strong> starting dialysis tend to do better — fewer hospital stays, better dialysis
      access, and more time to plan. So the earlier you're connected to care, the smoother the start.</p>

      <h2>What to bring to your first visit</h2>
      <ul style="line-height:1.9">
        <li><strong>Lab results from the past 12 months</strong> (or longer) — the trend over time matters more than one value.</li>
        <li><strong>A full list of everything you take</strong> — prescriptions, over-the-counter medicines, supplements and herbal remedies, with doses.</li>
        <li><strong>Notes on your symptoms</strong> — swelling, urine changes, tiredness, when they started and what makes them better or worse.</li>
        <li><strong>Home blood-pressure readings</strong>, if you have them — about a week of morning and evening readings is ideal.</li>
        <li><strong>Previous imaging</strong> (ultrasound / CT reports) and a valid ID and your PhilHealth Member Data Record (MDR).</li>
        <li><strong>A trusted companion</strong> — a spouse, adult child or friend to listen with you.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="notice"><strong>Please don't stop your medicines before the visit</strong> unless a doctor
      told you to. Your care team needs to see how you're doing on your current treatment.</div>

      <h2>During a dialysis session</h2>
      <p>You'll sit in a comfortable chair while the machine gently cleans your blood over a few hours.
      Many patients rest, read, or watch something. <strong>Our nurses monitor you the whole time</strong>,
      and a physician is on duty during clinic hours.</p>

      <h2>Afterwards</h2>
      <p>Most people go home and carry on with their day. Over the first weeks, dialysis becomes a familiar
      routine rather than an event. Our renal dietitian and social worker are on hand to help with diet,
      PhilHealth and the practical worries along the way.</p>

      <p style="margin-top:20px"><a href="/new-patients#request" class="btn btn--primary">Request your first visit</a></p>
